==English==

===Etymology===
From an [[Arabic]] verb ''[[giz]]''. {{rfscript|Arabic}}

===Verb===
{{infl|en|verb}}

# {{rfv-sense}} To [[hang]] around, [[flirt]] and do nothing [[productive]].
# {{dialect|archaic}} To [[grin]] and [[laugh]] (at another).
#*'''1875.''' ''The Gentleman's Magazine'',  Page 253 [http://books.google.com/books?id=a-oIAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA253&dq=gizzing+at+you&lr=&ei=z-G2Sq_-OI3YkQTX1onsDw#v=onepage&q=gizzing%20at%20you&f=false]:
#*:Nay then; but you're a '''gizzing''' at me, maister.
# {{dialect|UK}} To [[gaze]]

===Quotations===
*'''2004.''' Patricia Page. ''Across the magic line: growing up in Fiji''‎, page 197:
*:"But I knew dear, somebody else was '''gizzing''' you".

